<h2 id="nas-vs-cloud-storage">NAS vs Cloud Storage</h2>

<p>Building a NAS is like having a personal cloud storage center. Cloud storage is great, but you‚Äôre relying on someone else to access all of your data.</p>

<p>If you‚Äôre storing sensitive information and/or don‚Äôt like the idea of depending on a third party, using a NAS is a great way to eliminate that issue.</p>

<p>Moreover, NAS storage solutions may be a bit more costly to set up, but will save you hundreds if not thousands of dollars in the long run.</p>

<p>Cloud storage solutions can get expensive, and the more you scale, the more money you‚Äôve got to shell out just to store your data.</p>

<h2 id="nas-vs-external-hard-drive">NAS vs External Hard Drive</h2>

<p>Most people will initially buy an external hard drive or two after their PC starts filling up.</p>

<p>At first, external drives seem like a sound solution. They‚Äôre cheap, easy, and portable ‚Äî perfect for taking with you on the go, too.</p>

<p>But if you‚Äôre editing massive amounts of 4K video or have a ton of data that needs to be stored, external drives aren‚Äôt going to cut it.</p>

<p>You‚Äôll find them stacking in your office faster than you know what to do with them. Before you‚Äôll know it, you may find yourself owning a mount everest sized pile of them.</p>

<p>Worse still, they can only be accessed from one device at a time.</p>

<p>If you‚Äôve got several computers/devices in your home or office, it can quickly become a pain to plug your drive into each computer over and over.</p>

<p>Instead, it‚Äôs far more convenient to access all of your data from one centralized location.</p>

<p>This way, you can access your files from a PC, laptop, Mac, or even a phone, as long as you‚Äôre connected to the network.</p>

<p>Again, external drives are a good solution and are easily portable, but can quickly become obsolete when you‚Äôve got too much data to deal with.</p>

<h2 id="do-you-need-a-nas-case">Do You Need a NAS Case?</h2>

<p>If you find yourself constantly buying new storage solutions ‚Äî whether internal or external ‚Äî and always running out of space, a NAS is probably a good idea.</p>

<p>Rather than paying for expensive cloud storage that gets painfully expensive as you scale, a NAS is like your own personal cloud storage solution in your home or office.</p>

<p>It‚Äôs perfect for video editors/producers, and anyone who needs massive amounts of storage on a regular basis.</p>

<p>Instead of creating a mountain of external hard drives, buying (or building, in this case) a NAS storage solution is a much better option.</p>

<p>Not only is it more secure and scalable, but it‚Äôs also accessible across multiple platforms and devices in your home or office.</p>

<p>External storage can only be accessed by one computer at a time since it needs to be plugged in before use ‚Äî conversely, a NAS is accessible by every device on the network, no matter where you are or what operating system you‚Äôre using (Windows, Mac, IOS, etc).</p>

<p>If you‚Äôre using several TB of storage in your PC and still don‚Äôt have enough room, or have sensitive data you want to secure and back up on your own server, a NAS is a terrific idea.</p>

<p>However, buying a prebuilt NAS system can be pretty expensive (upwards of $800-$1000 dollars). Builders on a budget can build their own NAS system with the use of a NAS case and a bit more time.</p>

